@@bTidemouth Trail, Dune Fork@@N~
@@bThe trail breaks apart at this low rise, where wind has built a sand barrier just high enough to divide foot traffic into two channels.@@N To the north, a harder surface of compressed gravel and shell grit leads up into the @@bdune ridges@@N visible against the sky — the high-dune path that Glasswalk Guides prefer for its stable footing. To the south, the ground drops into a brackish depression where tidal infiltration has softened the sand and left a mirror-flat expanse of standing water at high tide. @@lGull cries carry from the east, and the damp smell of the tidal flat is unmistakable to the south.@@N The fork is marked with a pair of stacked cairn stones, one painted with a horizontal stripe of red ochre to indicate the wet-flat route and one left bare for the dune passage.
