@@bCrab Burrow Field@@N~
@@lThe tidal flat here is so heavily colonised by tidemouth crabs that the ground is effectively hollow in places — a sheet of crusted sand over a network of burrow tunnels.@@N A wrong step collapses a section of the surface, dropping one leg into a crab chamber where the occupant responds with the instinctive violence of something defending its tunnel. @@bThe crabs themselves are grey-tan, the size of a large boot, with claws that work in a scissors motion designed for seizing and crushing rather than for speed.@@N The smell of the flat is sharper here due to the decomposing organic material the crabs carry into their burrows. Moving through this area slowly and watching for the dark concentric rings that mark burrow exits is the only safe approach.
